<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
The species is distributed from northern and eastern Europe through Siberia, northern China, Mongolia, the Korean peninsula, and Sakhalin to Japan (
<bibRefCitation author="Danilevsky, ML" journalOrPublisher="HSC, Moscow" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" publicationUrl="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" refId="B11" refString="Danilevsky, ML, 2017a. Catalogue of Palaearctic Cerambycoidea. [Updated: 15.02.2017] http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" title="Catalogue of Palaearctic Cerambycoidea. [Updated: 15.02.2017]" url="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" year="2017 a">Danilevsky 2017a</bibRefCitation>
). In Europe, this species is strictly protected by European law. Although 
<taxonomicName authority="Nakane &amp; Ohbayashi, 1957" authorityName="Nakane &amp; Ohbayashi" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Creutzer" baseAuthorityYear="1799" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Macroleptura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macroleptura thoracica" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thoracica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Macroleptura thoracica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is mostly polyphagous on deciduous trees (
<bibRefCitation author="Svacha, P" journalOrPublisher="Biologica" pageId="26" pageNumber="133" pagination="1 - 205" refId="B64" refString="Svacha, P, Danilevsky, ML, 1989. Cerambycoid larvae of Europe and Soviet Union (Coleoptera, Cerambycoidea). Part III. Acta Universitatis Carolinae. Biologica 32 (1-2): 1 - 205" title="Cerambycoid larvae of Europe and Soviet Union (Coleoptera, Cerambycoidea). Part III. Acta Universitatis Carolinae." volume="32" year="1989">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Švácha">Svacha</normalizedToken>
and Danilevsky 1989
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Sama, G" journalOrPublisher="Kabourek, Zlin" pageId="25" pageNumber="132" refId="B61" refString="Sama, G, 2002. Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals. Kabourek, Zlin" title="Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals." year="2002">Sama 2002</bibRefCitation>
), it was also observed on the fir 
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Abies" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Abies" order="Pinales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Abies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. in Japan (
<bibRefCitation author="Sama, G" journalOrPublisher="Kabourek, Zlin" pageId="25" pageNumber="132" refId="B61" refString="Sama, G, 2002. Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals. Kabourek, Zlin" title="Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals." year="2002">Sama 2002</bibRefCitation>
). The species inhabits the dead, rotten wood of thick trunks. The adults fly from June to August and usually stay on their host plants; they rarely visit flowers (
<bibRefCitation author="Sama, G" journalOrPublisher="Kabourek, Zlin" pageId="25" pageNumber="132" refId="B61" refString="Sama, G, 2002. Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals. Kabourek, Zlin" title="Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals." year="2002">Sama 2002</bibRefCitation>
). In Mongolia, this is rare species that is not numerous (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Namhaidorzh, B" journalOrPublisher="Academy of Sciences of the USSR, Zoological Institute and Academie of Sciences of the MPR, Institute of Biology: Insects of Mongolia, Leningrad" pageId="25" pageNumber="132" pagination="495 - 538" refId="B51" refString="Namhaidorzh, B, 1972. On the fauna of longicorn beetles (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) of the Mongolian People's Republic. Academy of Sciences of the USSR, Zoological Institute and Academie of Sciences of the MPR, Institute of Biology: Insects of Mongolia, Leningrad 1: 495 - 538" title="On the fauna of longicorn beetles (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) of the Mongolian People's Republic." volume="1" year="1972">Namhaidorzh 1972</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Namhaidorzh, B" journalOrPublisher="Academy of Sciences of the USSR, Zoological Institute and Academie of Sciences of the MPR, Institute of Biology: Insects of Mongolia, Leningrad" pageId="25" pageNumber="132" pagination="202 - 216" refId="B53" refString="Namhaidorzh, B, 1976a. On the fauna of longicorn beetles (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) of the Mongolian People's Republic, II. Academy of Sciences of the USSR, Zoological Institute and Academie of Sciences of the MPR, Institute of Biology: Insects of Mongolia, Leningrad 4: 202 - 216" title="On the fauna of longicorn beetles (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) of the Mongolian People's Republic, II." volume="4" year="1976 a">1976a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
The remains of two specimens were found deep in the wood of the trunk of the stately poplar 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Populus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Populus tremula" order="Salicales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="tremula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Populus tremula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
together with numerous larval feeding grounds. This primeval forest relict species, which is very rare in Europe, appears to be rather numerous in this region. This indicates the high degree of the naturalness of the Mongolian habitats.
</paragraph>
